/*
:name: latch_reset
:type: equiv
:verilog_top: latch_reset.lrst8
:pyrope_top: lrst8
*/

// todo/livehd/2f-latch M7 — a latch with a RESET value.
//
// A latch's reset is inherently ASYNCHRONOUS: there is no clock edge to
// synchronize to, so it is emitted as the FIRST branch, ahead of the
// transparency test — the $adlatch shape:
//
//     always_latch begin
//       if (reset)   q <= <initial>;
//       else if (en) q <= d;
//     end
//
// Two things had to change for this to work at all, and both were the same
// class of bug this task keeps turning up — a value wired somewhere nothing
// reads it:
//   * `tree_declares_reset_reg` keyed on declare mode "reg", so a latch with a
//     reset value never caused the module's reset PORT to be created and the
//     compile died with "has a reset value but <mod> has no reset input
//     (setup_io bug)" — the reg was real, the port was never made;
//   * tolg then had to stop REFUSING the reset family on a latch and let it
//     fall through to the SHARED flop wiring, and cgen's process_latch had to
//     actually emit it. Wiring it without the emit would only have moved the
//     silent drop from tolg to cgen, which is the opposite of what M0 bought.
//
// The golden pins the reset VALUE, not just its presence: lgcheck REFUTES this
// design against an otherwise identical golden that resets to 7 instead of 3
// (verified), so the PROVEN below is not vacuous.
pub mod lrst8(en:bool, d:u8) -> (q:u8@[0]) {
  reg l:u8:[latch=true] = 3
  if en {
    l = d
  }
  q = l
}
